<p><b>Edward Wadie Saïd</b> <a href="/wiki/Royal_Society_of_Literature" title="Royal Society of Literature">MRSL</a> (<a href="/wiki/Arabic_language" title="Arabic language">Arabic</a>: <span lang="ar" xml:lang="ar"><b>إدوارد وديع سعيد</b></span>‎, <a href="/wiki/Romanization_of_Arabic" title="Romanization of Arabic">transliteration</a>: <span lang="ar-Latn" title="Arabic transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="ar-Latn"><b>Idwārd Wadīʿ Saʿīd</b></span>; <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1935-11-01"><a href="/wiki/November_1" title="November 1">1 November</a> <a href="/wiki/1935" title="1935">1935</a></span> – <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2003-09-25"><a href="/wiki/September_25" title="September 25">25 September</a> <a href="/wiki/2003" title="2003">2003</a></span>) was a <a href="/wiki/Palestinian_American" title="Palestinian American">Palestinian American</a> <a href="/wiki/Literary_theory" title="Literary theory">literary theorist</a>, political activist, intellectual warrior, <a href="/wiki/Cultural_critic" title="Cultural critic">cultural critic</a>, and an outspoken advocate for <a href="/wiki/Palestinian" title="Palestinian">Palestinian</a> rights. He was University Professor of English and Comparative Literature at <a href="/wiki/Columbia_University" title="Columbia University">Columbia University</a>. He was a founding figure in <a href="/wiki/Postcolonial_theory" title="Postcolonial theory" class="mw-redirect">postcolonial theory</a><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and during his lifetime was referred to as <a href="/wiki/Palestine" title="Palestine">Palestine</a>'s "most powerful political voice."<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
